      "title": "Payments, Inventory & Parallel Work",
      "content": "PAYMENTS: Extract as standalone service (the one true microservice in hybrid approach). The tangling IS the argument for extraction \u2014 late extraction forces other services/modules to build around monolith payment state. PCI nervousness addressed by separating code risk from compliance scope: extraction shrinks audit surface from entire monolith to one bounded service (~80% scope reduction with processor vault). Pre-extraction: migrate to processor vault if not done (SAQ-D to SAQ A-EP). Sub-phases: ACL inside monolith (weeks 11-12), data isolation (weeks 13-15), network boundary extraction (weeks 16-18), PCI hardening + cutover (weeks 19-20). Actual payment surface ~20% of perceived \u2014 most tendrils are orchestration logic. Payments extraction will require security audit \u2014 start audit process during build phase. INVENTORY: 3-week Postgres extraction approved if API is clean. DynamoDB REJECTED for bundling with extraction \u2014 realistic DynamoDB estimate 8-12 weeks, not 3. Likely real need is Redis cache for hot SKU reads. MODULAR MONOLITH CONTEXT: inventory stays as module with clean boundaries unless scaling demands extraction. PARALLEL SERVICES TRACK (while auth runs): create InventoryService interface inside monolith (1-2 weeks, zero risk), separate inventory data access (2-3 weeks), map read vs write patterns (1 week analysis), document order state machine (3-5 days), identify domain events (1 week), extract notifications as first real extraction (2-3 weeks, proves event bus). Notification extraction is ideal first extraction: fire-and-forget, no PCI/auth scope, forces event bus to be built. Priority if bandwidth limited: inventory interface > order state machine docs > domain events > notification extraction. CONSISTENCY MODEL: Payments team's concern about eventual consistency is correct but addressed by hybrid architecture. Strong consistency is per-service, not cross-service. Payment charge+record is ACID within payments service boundary. Cross-boundary coordination uses three patterns: (1) idempotency keys on every payment call (prevents double-charge), (2) reservation timeouts (prevents phantom inventory locks, self-healing), (3) reconciliation job every 5 min (catches edge cases). In hybrid architecture, only ONE cross-service boundary exists (monolith\u2192payments), so full saga pattern is unnecessary. Orders+inventory can still use local transactions within monolith. The best distributed transaction is the one you don't need.",
